### CSS Selectors

**Selectors** target HTML elements to apply styles.

---

### Basic Selectors

| Selector | Example | Targets |
|----------|---------|---------|
| **Element** | `p` | All `<p>` elements |
| **Class** | `.intro` | Elements with `class="intro"` |
| **ID** | `#logo` | Element with `id="logo"` |
| **Universal** | `*` | All elements |
| **Group** | `h1, h2` | Multiple selectors |

---

### Examples

```css
/* Element selector */
p {
  color: blue;
}

/* Class selector */
.highlight {
  background-color: yellow;
}

/* ID selector */
#header {
  font-size: 24px;
}

/* Universal selector */
* {
  margin: 0;
  padding: 0;
}

/* Group selector */
h1, h2, h3 {
  font-weight: bold;
}
```

---

### Combining Selectors

```css
/* Element with class */
p.important {
  color: red;
}

/* Multiple classes */
.box.dark {
  background: #333;
  color: white;
}

/* Descendant */
div p {
  margin: 10px;
}
```

---

### Nesting (Modern CSS)

```css
.card {
  background: white;

  & .title {
    font-size: 1.5em;
  }

  & .body {
    padding: 1rem;
  }
}
```

> **Best Practice:** Use classes (`.name`) for reusable styles. Use IDs (`#name`) for unique elements only.
